A startup has shipped a product for 18 months with no automated tests. A production bug slipped through last week and affected paying customers. We are debating whether to continue shipping with manual QA only, or pause feature work for two weeks to establish a test foundation before the next release. What should we do?

codex
Pause feature work for two weeks and build a **minimum test foundation**.

Manual QA-only after a customer-impacting prod bug is a bad risk tradeoff. You don’t need “full test coverage,” but you do need guardrails before the next release.

Recommended approach:

1. Freeze new features (allow only urgent revenue/security fixes).
2. In 2 weeks, deliver a thin but high-leverage test baseline:
- CI pipeline running on every PR
- Smoke tests for core paid user journeys
- Regression tests for last week’s incident and top 5 historical bug classes
- Contract/integration tests for the most failure-prone boundaries (billing, auth, critical APIs)
- PR rule: no merge without passing tests + bugfix includes a test
3. Resume feature work with this rule: each new feature ships with tests for critical paths.

This gives you a fast reduction in customer risk without trying to “boil the ocean.” If helpful, I can outline a day-by-day 10-business-day implementation plan.
